More than 7,377 Lancasters, 430 of which were built in Canada, were built during the Second World War but many that survived were scrapped.

It was the most successful bomber used by the Royal Air Force and the Royal Canadian Air Force.

In 1940, Prime Minister Winston Churchill threw his support behind the Royal Air Force's Fighter Command and the development of Bomber Command, stating: 'The Navy can lose us the war, but only the Air Force can win it. 

'Therefore our supreme effort must be to gain overwhelming mastery in the air.

'The Fighters are our salvation, but the Bombers alone provide the means of victory.'

The Lancaster Vera - built two years after the raids, in 1945 - was acquired by Canadian Warplane Heritage Museum in 1978 and underwent a 10-year restoration.

Vera - dedicated to Andrew Mynarski, the last Canadian airman to be awarded the VC in World War II – made the long journey to Britain from its base at the Ontario's Warplane Heritage Museum at the beginning of August. 

